title: For Sale:  "Colt 1911" beware!
postcontent:
This is a response to this ad placed earlier today:
http://www.armslist.com/posts/1292185/gainesville-florida-handguns-for-sale--colt-45-acp-marrk-iv-70-series-government-model-stainless-steel

FOR THE SAKE OF CLARITY, I HAVE COPIED THE ORIGINAL POST AS FOLLOWS:
"As title says .. colt mark iv 70 series stainless steel 1911
Good condition have 3 magazines. They hold 14. Rounds
Also can include ammo depending on offer. Will to trade plus cash or just
Trade. Or just sell .. make a offer. And please dont waste either of are time with a ridiculous
Offer this is a high quality gun and high capacity .. not many around for sale.
Any questions or offers text 352-278-4929 ."

For those of you who may not be familiar with the 1911 pistols, this is a warning that this ad is for a "Frankenstein" 1911. Colt NEVER has made a high capacity 1911 pistol. The only part of this gun that is of Colt production is the slide, and because of it being a series 70, we can guess it came from a Colt manufactured prior to 1983 when its production line was cancelled.
The frame and parts of this gun that you can see in the picture are not of colt manufacture, but instead this "high quality and rare" gun is a home-built collaboration of cheap and mismatched parts. The rear sight is not even for a 1911 pistol, and hangs out over the back of the slide. The front sight is what appears to be a "glue on" home job of some type or another. The beavertail safety does not match the frame, and considering how low it is sitting in the frame, is probably disabled or does not work at all. You can see by examining the pictures that the seller has "rubbed out" the marking on the barrel so you cannot see its stamping, and the manufacturers label on the frame has been edited so it cannot be read as well. I am guessing that it may be an older Caspian high capacity frame, but it could be one that was bought unfinished such as this one:
http://www.gunbroker.com/Auction/ViewItem.aspx?Item=333040302. or possibly an el-cheapo RIA frame from the Philippines.

I would steer clear of this obvious scam, but if you are desperate, please do not pay more than a couple hundred bucks for the sum of its hashed-together parts, as it is quite likely that most have been damaged beyond use. Better yet, report obvious scammer's like this one and get it removed before an un-knowledgeable buyer gets ripped off. 
When you see an obviously photo-shopped pic, run for the hills!

title: For Sale:  Ammo Lul
postcontent:
These prices are just stupid. Ok... Most places still sell ammo at reasonable prices. 380ACP $15-$18   9mm $12-$16   .40 $15-$18   .45 $20-25 (per 50 and all at brass prices.)
Why are people posting ammo for so much? Your only hindering the supply and causing the price to temperamentally to jump. Ammo is coming back in stock slowly and soon all of you that just went out and bought hundreds in ammo hoping to make a buck soon will have to take a hit. I work for a major retailer and ammo just hit our shelves this past week. I was able to get some 9's for 12 dollars a box. A box of .40 for $15 and just last night was able to get some 22's 100 packs for 8 dollars! There was and is no ammo shortage. Just stupid people trying to make money off stupid people. And for the people buying this ammo... Why not just shop around? Are you planning to go to the range in the next day that you have to have ammo now? The dumbest people are the ones who justify this stupid buying as "My rights might be taken away and that's why I'm doing it." Why? Ammo was never the cause of concern. They are and always will be targeting the guns. 
   Don't take it from me... All I can say is I have "enough" ammo and never spent more then 18 dollars on a single box and that was for my 45's. All my ammo acquired during this "ammo scare." I know no one will care but figured I should let people know that ammo is coming back. Go ahead and keep stock piling. People like me will only keep buying ammo before you can and selling what I don't need/want to people who need it at the cost to me and not 10 dollars over. 9's Should never be over $15 unless they are +p or JHP and for 22's if its not match ammo it's not worth more then $10 for 100. We want our freedom to own firearms in peace but sites like this prove that "we the people..." are just as greedy as the fat cats in the capital. Please show respect and show your fellow shooters respect. If ammo is this expensive people will stop shooting. Less shooters = less support when it comes to gun rights.
   Go ahead and flag this. This is just a friendly wake up call to everyone trying to make a dollar and for the ones getting soaked. Let the stores recover. There will be ammo. Only people who should be scared is congress when we stand up to them if they try to take our guns away in the future.
   Another thing I keep seeing is bulk ammo. For example, the bucket of 1400 Remington 22's ran me $80 at Cabelas! Not $100+! The 500/525 packs run about 30-40. Anything more is a scam. Also federals in the red box (The ones that have a WMxxxx number on the side) are walmart exclusives and only cost $14.
   I've actually gotten alot of positive feedback for my post. I will say though I'm not mad at people trying to make money. This is their right in a capitalistic society. But there are other places to make even better money.

title: For Trade:  NEW PPS 43 (8)/35 ROUND MAGAZINES 202 7.62 X 25 ROUNDS
postcontent:
Brand New I.O. Inc Polish PPS-43C pistol is chambered in 7.62x25 Tokarev and makes a fun range plinker. This pistol is manufactured at the famed Radom Plant in Poland from new Polish made parts and components. 

Specifications and Features: 
Caliber: 7.62x25 Tokarev 
Weight: 6.7 lbs empty 
Length: 24" 
Barrel length 9.84" 
Magazine (8) 35 rounds 

The History... 
The PPS-43C (Pistolet-Pulemet Sudaeva, model of 1943 = Sudaev SMG) was born as an answer to the need for a weapon that is more compact and mobile than the PPSh-41, then in use by the Soviet Army. The PPSh-41 was somewhat too long to be used by tank crews and mobile recon groups and paratroopers, so late in 1941, the Red Army issued a request for a new more compact sub machine gun (SMG). The designer Sudaev initially designed his new SMG in 1942, and it was adopted under the designation of PPS-42. The next year he refined the design, and this final model was designated as the PPS-43. This model was manufactured in significant numbers (nearly two million PPS-43 weapons were manufactured between 1943 and 1946). The PPS-43 is sometimes referred to as the best SMG of World War II. After WWII, it was widely exported to pro-Soviet regimes around the world, and widely copied. 

Today... 
I.O. Inc. redesigned this historical firearm to shoot from a closed bolt position. The safety is located at the front of the triggerguard. The receiver and barrel shroud are made from stamped steel. The rear sight is an L-shaped flip type and is marked for 100 and 200 meters, the front sight is a fixed blade type. The barrel is equipped with a simple muzzle brake. This firearm is an ATF approved pistol.

ANY CASH OFFER WELCOME
